{"title_page": "Visual Science (game company)", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Visual Sciences Limited\n| logo = Visual Science logo.svg\n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| industry = [[Video game industry|Video games]]\n| fate = [[Administration (law)|Administration]]\n| founded = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1993}}\n| founder = Russell Kay\n| defunct = {{End date|df=yes|2006|02}}\n| hq_location_city = [[Dundee]]\n| hq_location_country = Scotland\n| key_people = {{Unbulleted list|class=nowrap\n| Russell Kay:\n| [[Managing director|MD]] (1993\u20132005)\n| [[Chief technical officer|CTO]] (2005\u20132006)\n| Tim Christian:\n| [[Non-executive chairman]] (2003\u20132005)\n| [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] (2005\u20132006)\n}}\n| products =\n| owner = Tim Christian\n| num_employees = >100\n| num_employees_year = 2006\n}}\n\n'''Visual Sciences Limited''' (later branded as '''Visual Science''') was a British [[video game developer]] based in [[Dundee]] and founded in 1993 by former [[DMA Design]] employee Russel Kay. Kay sold a [[controlling interest]] in the studio to Tim Christian\u2014who had previously been hired as a [[non-executive chairman]]\u2014in January 2005, with Christian becoming its [[chief executive officer]]. Following the cancellation of a project by [[Vivendi Universal Games]] and Visual Science's subsequent inability to secure further funding led to it entering [[Administration (law)|administration]] and laying off all staff in February 2006.\n\n== History ==\nVisual Sciences was established in 1993 by Russell Kay, a former employee of [[DMA Design]] and the creator DMA's 1991 game ''[[Lemmings (video game)|Lemmings]]''.<ref name=\"GIbiz Vivendi\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/visual-science-to-launch-legal-action-against-vivendi |title=Visual Science to launch legal action against Vivendi |first=Ellie |last=Gibson |date=7 February 2006 |website=[[GamesIndustry.biz]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Visual Science hired Tim Christian (a former [[managing director]] of [[MicroProse]] and [[Hasbro Interactive]]) and Andy Campbell (a former managing director of [[Red Lemon]]) as [[non-executive chairman]] and [[commercial director]], respectively.<ref name=\"GIbiz Vivendi\" /><ref name=\"Gamasutra turnover\">{{cite web |url=https://gamasutra.com/view/news/95035/Visual_Science_Reports_Strong_Turnover.php |title=Visual Science Reports Strong Turnover |first=David |last=Jenkins |date=23 July 2004 |website=[[Gamasutra]]}}</ref> During Christian's tenure in this role, Visual Science recorded high revenue growth and the addition of large [[video game publisher]]s to its clients.<ref name=\"GIbiz Vivendi\" /> By July 2004, the company had also doubled its staff count to 75 in its [[Dundee]] headquarters and [[Los Angeles]] satellite office.<ref name=\"Gamasutra turnover\" /> In January 2005, Christian acquired 55% of the company's shares\u2014a [[controlling interest]]\u2014from Kay. Christian, therefore, became Visual Science's [[chief executive officer]], while Kay assumed the role of [[chief technical officer]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/tim-christian-takes-the-helm-at-visual-science |title=Tim Christian takes the helm at Visual Science |first=Rob |last=Fahey |date=14 January 2005 |website=[[GamesIndustry.biz]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fasttrack.co.uk/company_profile/visual-science/ |title=Visual Science |date=2005 |website=[[Sunday Times Fast Track 100|Fast Track]]}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2006, [[Vivendi Universal Games]] cancelled an unannounced project that Visual Science was developing, leaving the latter without funding. Visual Science had just moved into new Dundee offices for which it had not yet signed the lease. Christian informed the company's more than 100 staff to not leave personal belongings in the new building, fearing that the landlord could lock the team out as a result of the project's cancellation. Due to this, some employees believed that they were being laid off and the company shut down, however, Christian stated that this was not the case and that Visual Science would be pitching the project to other companies.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/visual-science-boss-quashes-closure-rumours |title=Visual Science boss quashes closure rumours |first=Rob |last=Fahey |date=27 January 2006 |website=[[GamesIndustry.biz]]}}</ref> As Visual Science could not find replacement work for the cancelled project, it filed for [[Administration (law)|administration]] by early February, laying off all employees. Christian stated that he was seeking to use the proceeds generated through the administration process to initiate legal action against Vivendi Universal Games, which he believed had terminated their contract baselessly.<ref name=\"GIbiz Vivendi\" /> Some former Visual Science employees went on to found Cohort Studios in 2006 and release its first game\u2014''[[Buzz! Junior: Dino Den]]''\u2014in February 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mcvuk.com/development-news/adundee-is-hurt-but-weall-come-back-strongera%c2%9d/ |title=\"Dundee is hurt, but we'll come back stronger\" |first=Billy |last=Thomson |date=21 October 2010 |website=[[MCV/Develop]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mcvuk.com/business-news/publishing/cohort-cheers-latest-ps2-release/ |title=Cohort cheers latest PS2 release |author=MCV Staff |date=18 November 2008 |website=[[MCV/Develop]]}}</ref> Other ex-employees founded [[Proper Games]], also in 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/gamesblog/2009/jan/14/xbox-playstation |title=Flock and the art of downloadable game development |first=Keith |last=Stuart |date=14 January 2009 |website=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1993 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:2006 disestablishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Dundee]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Defunct video game companies]]\n[[Category:Video game companies disestablished in 2006]]\n[[Category:Video game companies established in 1993]]\n[[Category:Video game companies of the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Visual Sciences Limited\n| logo = Visual Science logo.svg\n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| industry = [[Video game industry|Video games]]\n| fate = [[Administration]]\n| founded = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1993}}\n| founder = Russell Kay\n| defunct = {{End date|df=yes|2006|02}}\n| hq_location_city = [[Dundee]]\n| hq_location_country = Scotland\n| key_people = {{Unbulleted list|class=nowrap\n| Russell Kay:\n| [[Managing director|MD]] (1993\u20132005)\n| [[Chief technical officer|CTO]] (2005\u20132006)\n| Tim Christian:\n| [[Non-executive chairman]] (2003\u20132005)\n| [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] (2005\u20132006)\n}}\n| products =\n| owner = Tim Christian\n| num_employees = >100\n| num_employees_year = 2006\n}}\n\n'''Visual Sciences Limited''' (later branded as '''Visual Science''') was a British [[video game developer]] based in [[Dundee]] and founded in 1993 by former [[DMA Design]] employee Russel Kay. Kay sold a [[controlling interest]] in the studio to Tim Christian\u2014who had previously been hired as a [[non-executive chairman]]\u2014in January 2005, with Christian becoming its [[chief executive officer]]. Following the cancellation of a project by [[Vivendi Universal Games]] and Visual Science's subsequent inability to secure further funding led to it entering [[administration]] and laying off all staff in February 2006.\n\n== History ==\nVisual Sciences was established in 1993 by Russell Kay, a former employee of [[DMA Design]] and the creator DMA's 1991 game ''[[Lemmings (video game)|Lemmings]]''.<ref name=\"GIbiz Vivendi\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/visual-science-to-launch-legal-action-against-vivendi |title=Visual Science to launch legal action against Vivendi |first=Ellie |last=Gibson |date=7 February 2006 |website=[[GamesIndustry.biz]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Visual Science hired Tim Christian (a former [[managing director]] of [[MicroProse]] and [[Hasbro Interactive]]) and Andy Campbell (a former managing director of [[Red Lemon]]) as [[non-executive chairman]] and [[commercial director]], respectively.<ref name=\"GIbiz Vivendi\" /><ref name=\"Gamasutra turnover\">{{cite web |url=https://gamasutra.com/view/news/95035/Visual_Science_Reports_Strong_Turnover.php |title=Visual Science Reports Strong Turnover |first=David |last=Jenkins |date=23 July 2004 |website=[[Gamasutra]]}}</ref> During Christian's tenure in this role, Visual Science recorded high revenue growth and the addition of large [[video game publisher]]s to its clients.<ref name=\"GIbiz Vivendi\" /> By July 2004, the company had also doubled its staff count to 75 in its [[Dundee]] headquarters and [[Los Angeles]] satellite office.<ref name=\"Gamasutra turnover\" /> In January 2005, Christian acquired 55% of the company's shares\u2014a [[controlling interest]]\u2014from Kay. Christian, therefore, became Visual Science's [[chief executive officer]], while Kay assumed the role of [[chief technical officer]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/tim-christian-takes-the-helm-at-visual-science |title=Tim Christian takes the helm at Visual Science |first=Rob |last=Fahey |date=14 January 2005 |website=[[GamesIndustry.biz]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fasttrack.co.uk/company_profile/visual-science/ |title=Visual Science |date=2005 |website=[[Sunday Times Fast Track 100|Fast Track]]}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2006, [[Vivendi Universal Games]] cancelled an unannounced project that Visual Science was developing, leaving the latter without funding. Visual Science had just moved into new Dundee offices for which it had not yet signed the lease. Christian informed the company's more than 100 staff to not leave personal belongings in the new building, fearing that the landlord could lock the team out as a result of the project's cancellation. Due to this, some employees believed that they were being laid off and the company shut down, however, Christian stated that this was not the case and that Visual Science would be pitching the project to other companies.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/visual-science-boss-quashes-closure-rumours |title=Visual Science boss quashes closure rumours |first=Rob |last=Fahey |date=27 January 2006 |website=[[GamesIndustry.biz]]}}</ref> As Visual Science could not find replacement work for the cancelled project, it filed for [[administration]] by early February, laying off all employees. Christian stated that he was seeking to use the proceeds generated through the administration process to initiate legal action against Vivendi Universal Games, which he believed had terminated their contract baselessly.<ref name=\"GIbiz Vivendi\" /> Some former Visual Science employees went on to found Cohort Studios in 2006 and release its first game\u2014''[[Buzz! Junior: Dino Den]]''\u2014in February 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mcvuk.com/development-news/adundee-is-hurt-but-weall-come-back-strongera%c2%9d/ |title=\"Dundee is hurt, but we'll come back stronger\" |first=Billy |last=Thomson |date=21 October 2010 |website=[[MCV/Develop]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mcvuk.com/business-news/publishing/cohort-cheers-latest-ps2-release/ |title=Cohort cheers latest PS2 release |author=MCV Staff |date=18 November 2008 |website=[[MCV/Develop]]}}</ref> Other ex-employees founded [[Proper Games]], also in 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/gamesblog/2009/jan/14/xbox-playstation |title=Flock and the art of downloadable game development |first=Keith |last=Stuart |date=14 January 2009 |website=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1993 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:2006 disestablishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Dundee]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Defunct video game companies]]\n[[Category:Video game companies disestablished in 2006]]\n[[Category:Video game companies established in 1993]]\n[[Category:Video game companies of the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "IceWelder", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Visual_Science_(game_company)"}
{"title_page": "Trevilder", "text_new": "[[File:Trevilder Crossroads - geograph.org.uk - 448621.jpg|thumb|Trevilder crossroads]]\n'''Trevilder''' is a farm in the parish of [[Egloshayle]], [[Cornwall]], [[England]], UK.<ref>Ordnance Survey get-a-map SX0231872225</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n* [[List of farms in Cornwall]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Cornwall|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Farms in Cornwall]]\n\n{{Cornwall-geo-stub}}\n\n{{coord missing|Cornwall}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Trevilder Crossroads - geograph.org.uk - 448621.jpg|thumb|Trevilder crossroads]]\n'''Trevilder''' is a farm in the parish of [[Egloshayle]], [[Cornwall]], [[England]], UK.<ref>Ordnance Survey get-a-map SX0231872225</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of farms in Cornwall]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Cornwall|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Farms in Cornwall]]\n\n{{Cornwall-geo-stub}}\n\n{{coord missing|Cornwall}}\n", "name_user": "Gazamp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also:AddedPortal:Cornwall", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trevilder"}
{"title_page": "John McWhorter", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name=John McWhorter\n|image=JohnMcWhorter.jpg\n|caption=John McWhorter in 2008\n|birth_name=John Hamilton McWhorter V\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1965|10|6}}\n|birth_place= [[Philadelphia|Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n|fields=[[Linguistics]]\n|workplaces= {{plainlist|\n* [[Cornell University]]\n* [[UC Berkeley]]\n* [[Columbia University]]\n* [[Manhattan Institute for Policy Research|Manhattan Institute]]\n}}\n|alma_mater= {{plainlist|\n* [[Simon's Rock College]] <small>([[Associate degree|AA]])</small>\n* [[Rutgers University]] <small>([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])</small>\n* [[New York University]] <small>([[Master of Arts|MA]])</small>\n* [[Stanford University]] <small>([[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])</small>\n}}\n}}\n\n'''John Hamilton McWhorter V''' ({{IPAc-en|m|\u0259|k|\u02c8|hw|\u0254\u02d0r|t|\u0259r}};<ref>McWhorter, John H. \"[http://www.slate.com/articles/podcasts/lexicon_valley.html Lexicon Valley]\". ''Slate''. The Slate Group, a Graham Holdings Company. (Listen to McWhorter's pronunciation of his own name at the beginning of each podcast.)</ref> born October 6, 1965) is an American academic and [[linguist]] who is associate professor of English and comparative literature at [[Columbia University]], where he teaches linguistics, American studies, philosophy, and music history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/authors?author=John%20McWhorter|title=NY Daily News- Articles By John McWhorter|work=NY Daily News|accessdate=November 29, 2014}}</ref> He is the author of a number of books on language and on [[Sociology of race and ethnic relations|race relations]], and his writing has appeared in many prominent magazines. His research specializes on how [[creole language]]s form, and how language grammars change as the result of sociohistorical phenomena.\n\n==Early life==\nMcWhorter was born and raised in [[Philadelphia]]. His father, John Hamilton McWhorter IV (1927\u20131996)<ref>Word on the Street: Debunking the Myth of a Pure Standard English, John H. McWhorter V, Perseus Publishing, 1998</ref> was a college administrator, and his mother Schelysture Gordon McWhorter (1937\u20132011) taught social work at [[Temple University]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|last=Miller|first=Jason Philip|date=2006|isbn=9780195301731 |doi=10.1093/aasc/9780195301731.013.5211|title=McWhorter, John|work=African American National Biography|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York|editor1-last=Gates|editor1-first=Henry Louis|editor2-last=Higginbotham|editor2-first=Evelyn Brooks}}</ref><ref>Black Conservative Intellectuals in Modern America, Michael L. Ondaatje, University of Pennsylvania Press, 2010, p. 174</ref> He attended [[Friends Select School]] in [[Philadelphia]], and after [[tenth grade]] was accepted to [[Simon's Rock College]], where he earned an [[Associate's degree|A.A. degree]]. Later, he attended [[Rutgers University]] and received a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in [[French language|French]] in 1985. He received a [[master's degree]] in [[American Studies]] from [[New York University]] and a [[Ph.D.]] in linguistics in 1993 from [[Stanford University]].\n\n==Career==\n{{unreferenced section|date=May 2019}}\nSince 2008, he has taught linguistics, American studies, and classes in the core curriculum program at [[Columbia University]], where he is currently an associate professor in the English and comparative literature department. After graduation McWhorter was an [[associate professor]] of linguistics at [[Cornell University]] from 1993 to 1995 before taking up a position as associate professor of linguistics at the [[University of California, Berkeley]], from 1995 until 2003. He left that position to become a senior fellow at the [[Manhattan Institute]], a [[Conservatism|conservative]] [[think tank]]. He was contributing editor at ''[[The New Republic]]'' from 2001 to 2014. From 2006 to 2008 he was a columnist for the ''[[New York Sun]]'' and he has written columns regularly for ''[[The Root (magazine)|The Root]]'', ''[[The New York Daily News]]'', ''[[The Daily Beast]]'', [[CNN]] and Time Ideas.\n\nMcWhorter has published a number of books on linguistics and on race relations, of which the better known are ''Power of Babel: A Natural History of Language'', ''Our Magnificent Bastard Tongue: The Untold History of English'', ''Doing Our Own Thing: The Degradation of Language and Music and Why You Should, Like, Care'', and ''[[Losing the Race: Self-Sabotage in Black America]]''. He makes regular public radio and television appearances on related subjects. He is interviewed frequently on [[National Public Radio]] and is a frequent contributor on [[Bloggingheads.tv]] including ten years of discussions with [[Glenn Loury]]. He has appeared twice on ''[[Penn & Teller: Bullshit!]]'', once in the [[profanity]] episode in his capacity as a linguistics professor, and again in the [[Reparations for slavery|slavery reparations]] episode for his political views and knowledge of race relations. He has spoken at [[TED (conference)|TED]] (2013, 2016), has appeared on ''[[The Colbert Report]]'' and ''[[Real Time with Bill Maher]]'', and appeared regularly on [[MSNBC]]'s ''[[Up with Chris Hayes]]''.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nMcWhorter is the author of the courses \"The Story of Human Language\"; \"Understanding Linguistics: The Science of Language\"; \"Myths, Lies and Half-Truths About English Usage\"; \"Language Families of the World\"; and \"Language From A to Z\" in the series [[The Great Courses]], produced by the Teaching Company.\n\nA popular writer, McWhorter has written for ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', ''[[The Atlantic]]'', ''[[The Chronicle of Higher Education]]'', ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'', ''[[The New Republic]]'', ''[[Politico]]'', ''[[Forbes]]'', ''[[The Chicago Tribune]]'', ''[[The New York Daily News]]'', ''[[City Journal (New York)|City Journal]]'', ''[[The New Yorker]]'', among others; he is also [[contributing editor]] at ''[[The Atlantic]]'' and hosts ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]''{{'}}s ''Lexicon Valley'' podcast.\n\n==Linguistics==\nMuch of McWhorter's academic work is concerned with creoles and their relationship to other languages, often focusing on the [[Surinam]] creole language [[Saramaccan]]. His work has expanded to a general investigation of the effect of [[second-language acquisition]] on a language. He argues that languages naturally tend toward complexity and irregularity, a tendency that is reversed only by adults acquiring the language, and creole formation is simply an extreme example of the latter.<ref>{{cite book | title = Language Interrupted: Signs of Non-Native Acquisition in Standard Language Grammars | given = John | surname = McWhorter | publisher = Oxford University Press | year = 2007 | isbn = 978-0-198-04231-0 | pages = 5\u201318 }}</ref> As examples, he cites English, [[Mandarin Chinese]], [[Farsi language|Persian]], the modern colloquial [[varieties of Arabic]], [[Swahili language|Swahili]], and [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]]. He has outlined his ideas in academic format in ''Language Interrupted'' and ''Linguistic Simplicity and Complexity'' and, for the general public, in ''What Language Is'' and ''Our Magnificent Bastard Tongue''. Some other linguists suggest that his notions of simplicity and complexity are impressionistic and grounded on comparisons with [[European languages]] and they point to exceptions to the correlation that he proposes.<ref>{{cite book | title = Languages in Contact | given1 = Umberto | surname1 = Ansaldo | given2 = Lisa | surname2 = Lim | publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 2015 | isbn = 978-0-521-76795-8 | pages = 194\u2013195 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Review: ''Linguistic simplicity and complexity'' | given = Mauro | surname = Giuffr\u00e8 | website = LINGUIST List | at = 24.1461 | year = 2013 | url = http://linguistlist.org/issues/24/24-1461.html | access-date = 20 August 2016 }}</ref>\n\nMcWhorter is a vocal critic of the [[Sapir-Whorf hypothesis]]. In ''The Language Hoax'', he outlines his opposition to the notion that \"language channels thought.\"\n\nMcWhorter has also been a proponent of a theory that various languages on the island of [[Flores]] underwent transformation because of aggressive migrations from the nearby island of [[Sulawesi]], and he has joined scholars{{who|date=August 2019}} who contend that English was [[Brittonicisms in English|influenced]] by the [[Celtic languages]] spoken by the indigenous population and was then encountered by the [[Germanic invasions|Germanic invaders]] of Britain.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/english-language-and-linguistics/article/what-else-happened-to-english-a-brief-for-the-celtic-hypothesis/7E774117C3B14855E00C75C0726DD095|title=What else happened to English? A brief for the Celtic hypothesis|first=J. H.|last=McWhorter|date=July 10, 2009|journal=English Language & Linguistics|volume=13|issue=2|pages=163\u2013191|via=Cambridge Core|doi=10.1017/S1360674309002974}}</ref> He has also written various pieces for the media that argue that colloquial constructions, such as the modern uses of \"like\" and \"totally,\" and other non-standard speech should be considered alternative renditions of English rather than degraded ones.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/06/opinion/sunday/like-degrading-the-language-no-way.html|title=Opinion &#124; Like, Degrading the Language? No Way|first=John|last=McWhorter|date=April 5, 2014|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, McWhorter was one of the speakers in the [[Linguistic Society of America]]'s inaugural Public Lectures on Language series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.linguisticsociety.org/content/lsa-public-lectures-language-series|title=LSA Public Lectures on Language Series \u2013 Linguistic Society of America|website=www.linguisticsociety.org}}</ref>\n\n==Social and political views==\nMcWhorter characterizes himself as \"a cranky liberal [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]\". In support of this description, he states that while he \"disagree[s] sustainedly with many of the tenets of the Civil Rights orthodoxy,\" he also \"supports [[Barack Obama]], reviles the [[War on Drugs]], supports [[gay marriage]], never voted for [[George W. Bush|George Bush]] and writes of [[African American Vernacular English|Black English]] as coherent speech\". McWhorter additionally notes that the conservative [[Manhattan Institute]], for which he worked, \"has always been hospitable to Democrats\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/82122/frances-fox-piven-jim-sleeper-and-me |title=Frances Fox Piven, Jim Sleeper and Me |date=January 25, 2011 |last=McWhorter |first=John |work=[[The New Republic]]|accessdate=November 29, 2014}}</ref>  McWhorter has criticized left-wing and activist educators in particular, such as [[Paulo Freire]] and [[Jonathan Kozol]].<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Taking out My Eraser|magazine=[[The New Republic]]|last=McWhorter|first=John|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/politics/taking-out-my-eraser|date=March 5, 2010}}</ref> He believes that [[affirmative action]] should be based on class rather than race.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/12/13/opinions/mcwhorter-antonin-scalia-affirmative-action/ |title=Actually, Scalia had a point. |date=December 13, 2015 |last=McWhorter |first=John |work=[[CNN]]|accessdate=December 3, 2016}}</ref> Political theorist [[Mark Satin]] identifies McWhorter as a [[Radical center (politics)|radical centrist]] thinker.<ref>Satin, Mark (2004).  ''Radical Middle: The Politics We Need Now''. Westview Press and Basic Books, p.&nbsp;10.  {{ISBN|978-0-8133-4190-3}}.</ref> \n\nMcWhorter is an [[atheism|atheist]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/johnhmcwhorter/status/523438726786342912|title=John McWhorter on Twitter|date=October 18, 2014|last=McWhorter|first=John|accessdate=May 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Views on racism ===\nMcWhorter considers that [[anti-racism]] has become as harmful a force in the [[United States]] as [[racism]] itself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://reason.com/video/anti-racism-soho-debate/|title=Has Anti-Racism Become as Harmful as Racism? John McWhorter vs. Nikhil Singh|date=2018-11-30|website=Reason.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://reason.com/2018/11/09/the-message-of-anti-racism-has-become-as/|title=Debate: 'The Message of Anti-Racism Has Become as Harmful a Force in American Life as Racism Itself'|date=2018-11-09|website=Reason.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref> According to him, what is holding blacks back is \"black attitudes\" rather than white racism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.city-journal.org/html/what%E2%80%99s-holding-blacks-back-12025.html|title=What\u2019s Holding Blacks Back?|date=2015-12-23|website=City Journal|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, McWhorter appeared on [[NPR]] and claimed that the use of the word \"thug\" was becoming code for \"the [[Nigger#The N-word euphemism|N-word]]\" or \"black people ruining things\" when used by whites in reference to criminal activity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2015/04/30/403362626/the-racially-charged-meaning-behind-the-word-thug|title=The Racially Charged Meaning Behind The Word 'Thug'|author=All Things Considered|date=April 30, 2015|publisher=NPR|accessdate=November 25, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"WPThug\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/posteverything/wp/2015/05/01/baltimores-mayor-and-president-obama-said-thugs-lets-not-get-too-bent-out-of-shape/?postshare=7831430516681050|title=Baltimore\u2019s mayor and the president said \u2018thugs\u2019? Let\u2019s not get too bent out of shape.|last=McWhorter|first=John|newspaper=The Washington Post|accessdate=November 25, 2015}}</ref> He added that use by [[President Obama]] and former Baltimore Mayor [[Stephanie Rawlings-Blake]] (for which she later apologized) could not be interpreted in the same way, given that the black community's use of \"thug\" may positively connote admiration for black self-direction and survival. McWhorter clarified his views in an article in the ''Washington Post''.<ref name=\"WPThug\" />\n\nMcWhorter has criticized [[microaggression]] and [[white supremacy]] theories,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/32618/microaggression-is-the-new-racism-on-campus/|title='Microaggression' Is the New Racism on Campus|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/4584161/white-supremacy/|title=The Difference Between Racial Bias and White Supremacy|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref> and has argued that [[technology]] cannot be racist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/4475627/is-technology-capable-of-being-racist/|title='Racist' Technology Is a Bug\u2014Not a Crime|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{external media| float = right| video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?162197-1/authentically-black-essays-black-silent-majority ''Booknotes'' interview with McWhorter on ''Authentically Black: Essays for the Black Silent Majority'', March 2, 2003], [[C-SPAN]]| video2 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?202200-1/depth-john-mcwhorter ''In Depth'' interview with McWhorter, March 2, 2008], [[C-SPAN]]}}\n* 1997: ''Towards a New Model of Creole Genesis'' {{ISBN|0-820-43312-8}}\n* 1998: ''Word on the Street: Debunking the Myth of a \"Pure\" Standard English'' {{ISBN|0-738-20446-3}}\n* 2000: ''Spreading the Word: Language and Dialect in America'' {{ISBN|0-325-00198-7}}\n* 2000: ''The Missing Spanish Creoles: Recovering the Birth of Plantation Contact Languages'' {{ISBN|0-520-21999-6}}\n* 2000: ''[[Losing the Race|Losing the Race: Self-Sabotage in Black America]]'' {{ISBN|0-684-83669-6}}\n* 2001: ''The Power of Babel: A Natural History of Language'' {{ISBN|0-06-052085-X}}\n* 2003: ''Authentically Black: Essays for the Black Silent Majority'' {{ISBN|1-592-40001-9}}\n* 2003: ''Doing Our Own Thing: The Degradation of Language and Music and Why We Should, Like, Care'' {{ISBN|1-592-40016-7}}\n* 2005: ''Defining Creole'' {{ISBN|0-195-16669-8}}\n* 2005: ''Winning the Race: Beyond the Crisis in Black America'' {{ISBN|1-592-40188-0}}\n* 2007: ''Language Interrupted: Signs of Non-Native Acquisition in Standard Language Grammars'' {{ISBN|0-195-30980-4}}\n* 2008: ''All About the Beat: Why Hip-Hop Can't Save Black America'' {{ISBN|1-592-40374-3}}\n* 2008: ''Our Magnificent Bastard Tongue: The Untold History of English'' {{ISBN|1-592-40395-6}}\n* 2011: ''Linguistic Simplicity and Complexity: Why Do Languages Undress?'' {{ISBN|978-1-934-07837-2}}\n* 2011: ''What Language Is: (And What It Isn't and What It Could Be)'' {{ISBN|978-1-592-40625-8}}\n* 2012: ''A Grammar of Saramaccan Creole'' (co-authored with Jeff Good) {{ISBN|978-3-11-027643-5}}\n* 2014: ''The Language Hoax: Why the World Looks the Same in Any Language'' {{ISBN|978-0-199-36158-8}}\n* 2016: ''Words on the Move: Why English Won't \u2013 and Can't \u2013 Sit Still (Like, Literally)'' {{ISBN|978-1-627-79471-8}}\n* 2017: ''Talking Back, Talking Black: Truths about America's Lingua Franca'' {{ISBN|978-1-942-65820-7}}\n* 2018: ''The Creole Debate'' {{ISBN|978-1-108-42864-4}}\n* 2015\u20132019: [https://www.theatlantic.com/author/john-mcwhorter/ Columns in The Atlantic].\n\n== Video clips ==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=phsU1vVHOQI Donald Trump's Way Of Speaking is 'Oddly Adolescent'] \u2013 MSNBC\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a5mZ0R3h8m0 Are Elvish, Klingon, Dothraki and Na'vi real languages?] \u2013 TED-Ed\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VQRjouwKDlU 4 Reasons to Learn a New Language] \u2013 TED\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8hWQmzgiKXQ A Critical Look at the 1619 Project] \u2013 The Glenn Show\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.nysun.com/authors/John+Mcwhorter ''New York Sun'' columns]\n* [https://newrepublic.com/authors/john-mcwhorter McWhorter's blog at ''The New Republic'']\n* [http://bloggingheads.tv/?s=mcwhorter Video interviews and discussions with McWhorter] on [[bloggingheads.tv]]\n* {{C-SPAN|John McWhorter}}\n* [https://www.city-journal.org/html/what%E2%80%99s-holding-blacks-back-12025.html \"What's Holding Blacks Back?\"] by John H. McWhorter, ''[[City Journal (New York City)|City Journal]]'', Winter 2001\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mcwhorter, John}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American academics]]\n[[Category:African-American atheists]]\n[[Category:African-American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:African-American social scientists]]\n[[Category:American atheists]]\n[[Category:American social scientists]]\n[[Category:American social sciences writers]]\n[[Category:Linguists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Columbia University faculty]]\n[[Category:Cornell University faculty]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:New York University alumni]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania Democrats]]\n[[Category:Writers from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Radical centrist writers]]\n[[Category:Rutgers University alumni]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:Educators from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:20th-century linguists]]\n[[Category:21st-century linguists]]\n[[Category:Manhattan Institute for Policy Research]]\n[[Category:Friends Select School alumni]]\n[[Category:Linguists of pidgins and creoles]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name=John McWhorter\n|image=JohnMcWhorter.jpg\n|caption=John McWhorter in 2008\n|birth_name=John Hamilton McWhorter V\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1965|10|6}}\n|birth_place= [[Philadelphia|Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n|fields=[[Linguistics]]\n|workplaces= {{plainlist|\n* [[Cornell University]]\n* [[UC Berkeley]]\n* [[Columbia University]]\n* [[Manhattan Institute for Policy Research|Manhattan Institute]]\n}}\n|alma_mater= {{plainlist|\n* [[Simon's Rock College]] <small>([[Associate degree|AA]])</small>\n* [[Rutgers University]] <small>([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])</small>\n* [[New York University]] <small>([[Master of Arts|MA]])</small>\n* [[Stanford University]] <small>([[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])</small>\n}}\n}}\n\n'''John Hamilton McWhorter V''' ({{IPAc-en|m|\u0259|k|\u02c8|hw|\u0254\u02d0r|t|\u0259r}};<ref>McWhorter, John H. \"[http://www.slate.com/articles/podcasts/lexicon_valley.html Lexicon Valley]\". ''Slate''. The Slate Group, a Graham Holdings Company. (Listen to McWhorter's pronunciation of his own name at the beginning of each podcast.)</ref> born October 6, 1965) is an American academic and [[linguist]] who is associate professor of English and comparative literature at [[Columbia University]], where he teaches linguistics, American studies, philosophy, and music history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/authors?author=John%20McWhorter|title=NY Daily News- Articles By John McWhorter|work=NY Daily News|accessdate=November 29, 2014}}</ref> He is the author of a number of books on language and on [[Sociology of race and ethnic relations|race relations]], and his writing has appeared in many prominent magazines. His research specializes on how [[creole language]]s form, and how language grammars change as the result of sociohistorical phenomena.\n\n==Early life==\nMcWhorter was born and raised in [[Philadelphia]]. His father, John Hamilton McWhorter IV (1927\u20131996)<ref>Word on the Street: Debunking the Myth of a Pure Standard English, John H. McWhorter V, Perseus Publishing, 1998</ref> was a college administrator, and his mother Schelysture Gordon McWhorter (1937\u20132011) taught social work at [[Temple University]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|last=Miller|first=Jason Philip|date=2006|isbn=9780195301731 |doi=10.1093/aasc/9780195301731.013.5211|title=McWhorter, John|work=African American National Biography|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York|editor1-last=Gates|editor1-first=Henry Louis|editor2-last=Higginbotham|editor2-first=Evelyn Brooks}}</ref><ref>Black Conservative Intellectuals in Modern America, Michael L. Ondaatje, University of Pennsylvania Press, 2010, p. 174</ref> He attended [[Friends Select School]] in [[Philadelphia]], and after [[tenth grade]] was accepted to [[Simon's Rock College]], where he earned an [[Associate's degree|A.A. degree]]. Later, he attended [[Rutgers University]] and received a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in [[French language|French]] in 1985. He received a [[master's degree]] in [[American Studies]] from [[New York University]] and a [[Ph.D.]] in linguistics in 1993 from [[Stanford University]].\n\n==Career==\n{{unreferenced section|date=May 2019}}\nSince 2008, he has taught linguistics, American studies, and classes in the core curriculum program at [[Columbia University]], where he is currently an associate professor in the English and comparative literature department. After graduation McWhorter was an [[associate professor]] of linguistics at [[Cornell University]] from 1993 to 1995 before taking up a position as associate professor of linguistics at the [[University of California, Berkeley]], from 1995 until 2003. He left that position to become a senior fellow at the [[Manhattan Institute]], a [[Conservatism|conservative]] [[think tank]]. He was contributing editor at ''[[The New Republic]]'' from 2001 to 2014. From 2006 to 2008 he was a columnist for the ''[[New York Sun]]'' and he has written columns regularly for ''[[The Root (magazine)|The Root]]'', ''[[The New York Daily News]]'', ''[[The Daily Beast]]'', [[CNN]] and Time Ideas.\n\nMcWhorter has published a number of books on linguistics and on race relations, of which the better known are ''Power of Babel: A Natural History of Language'', ''Our Magnificent Bastard Tongue: The Untold History of English'', ''Doing Our Own Thing: The Degradation of Language and Music and Why You Should, Like, Care'', and ''[[Losing the Race: Self-Sabotage in Black America]]''. He makes regular public radio and television appearances on related subjects. He is interviewed frequently on [[National Public Radio]] and is a frequent contributor on [[Bloggingheads.tv]] including ten years of discussions with [[Glenn Loury]]. He has appeared twice on ''[[Penn & Teller: Bullshit!]]'', once in the [[profanity]] episode in his capacity as a linguistics professor, and again in the [[Reparations for slavery|slavery reparations]] episode for his political views and knowledge of race relations. He has spoken at [[TED (conference)|TED]] (2013, 2016), has appeared on ''[[The Colbert Report]]'' and ''[[Real Time with Bill Maher]]'', and appeared regularly on [[MSNBC]]'s ''[[Up with Chris Hayes]]''.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nMcWhorter is the author of the courses \"The Story of Human Language\"; \"Understanding Linguistics: The Science of Language\"; \"Myths, Lies and Half-Truths About English Usage\"; \"Language Families of the World\"; and \"Language From A to Z\" in the series [[The Great Courses]], produced by the Teaching Company.\n\nA popular writer, McWhorter has written for ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', ''[[The Atlantic]]'', ''[[The Chronicle of Higher Education]]'', ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'', ''[[The New Republic]]'', ''[[Politico]]'', ''[[Forbes]]'', ''[[The Chicago Tribune]]'', ''[[The New York Daily News]]'', ''[[City Journal (New York)|City Journal]]'', ''[[The New Yorker]]'', among others; he is also [[contributing editor]] at ''[[The Atlantic]]'' and hosts ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]''{{'}}s ''Lexicon Valley'' podcast.\n\n==Linguistics==\nMuch of McWhorter's academic work is concerned with creoles and their relationship to other languages, often focusing on the [[Surinam]] creole language [[Saramaccan]]. His work has expanded to a general investigation of the effect of [[second-language acquisition]] on a language. He argues that languages naturally tend toward complexity and irregularity, a tendency that is reversed only by adults acquiring the language, and creole formation is simply an extreme example of the latter.<ref>{{cite book | title = Language Interrupted: Signs of Non-Native Acquisition in Standard Language Grammars | given = John | surname = McWhorter | publisher = Oxford University Press | year = 2007 | isbn = 978-0-198-04231-0 | pages = 5\u201318 }}</ref> As examples, he cites English, [[Mandarin Chinese]], [[Farsi language|Persian]], the modern colloquial [[varieties of Arabic]], [[Swahili language|Swahili]], and [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]]. He has outlined his ideas in academic format in ''Language Interrupted'' and ''Linguistic Simplicity and Complexity'' and, for the general public, in ''What Language Is'' and ''Our Magnificent Bastard Tongue''. Some other linguists suggest that his notions of simplicity and complexity are impressionistic and grounded on comparisons with [[European languages]] and they point to exceptions to the correlation that he proposes.<ref>{{cite book | title = Languages in Contact | given1 = Umberto | surname1 = Ansaldo | given2 = Lisa | surname2 = Lim | publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 2015 | isbn = 978-0-521-76795-8 | pages = 194\u2013195 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Review: ''Linguistic simplicity and complexity'' | given = Mauro | surname = Giuffr\u00e8 | website = LINGUIST List | at = 24.1461 | year = 2013 | url = http://linguistlist.org/issues/24/24-1461.html | access-date = 20 August 2016 }}</ref>\n\nMcWhorter is a vocal critic of the [[Sapir-Whorf hypothesis]]. In ''The Language Hoax'', he outlines his opposition to the notion that \"language channels thought.\"\n\nMcWhorter has also been a proponent of a theory that various languages on the island of [[Flores]] underwent transformation because of aggressive migrations from the nearby island of [[Sulawesi]], and he has joined scholars{{who|date=August 2019}} who contend that English was [[Brittonicisms in English|influenced]] by the [[Celtic languages]] spoken by the indigenous population and was then encountered by the [[Germanic invasions|Germanic invaders]] of Britain.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/english-language-and-linguistics/article/what-else-happened-to-english-a-brief-for-the-celtic-hypothesis/7E774117C3B14855E00C75C0726DD095|title=What else happened to English? A brief for the Celtic hypothesis|first=J. H.|last=McWhorter|date=July 10, 2009|journal=English Language & Linguistics|volume=13|issue=2|pages=163\u2013191|via=Cambridge Core|doi=10.1017/S1360674309002974}}</ref> He has also written various pieces for the media that argue that colloquial constructions, such as the modern uses of \"like\" and \"totally,\" and other non-standard speech should be considered alternative renditions of English rather than degraded ones.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/06/opinion/sunday/like-degrading-the-language-no-way.html|title=Opinion &#124; Like, Degrading the Language? No Way|first=John|last=McWhorter|date=April 5, 2014|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, McWhorter was one of the speakers in the [[Linguistic Society of America]]'s inaugural Public Lectures on Language series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.linguisticsociety.org/content/lsa-public-lectures-language-series|title=LSA Public Lectures on Language Series \u2013 Linguistic Society of America|website=www.linguisticsociety.org}}</ref>\n\n==Social and political views==\nMcWhorter characterizes himself as \"a cranky liberal [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]\". In support of this description, he states that while he \"disagree[s] sustainedly with many of the tenets of the Civil Rights orthodoxy,\" he also \"supports [[Barack Obama]], reviles the [[War on Drugs]], supports [[gay marriage]], never voted for [[George W. Bush|George Bush]] and writes of [[African American Vernacular English|Black English]] as coherent speech\". McWhorter additionally notes that the conservative [[Manhattan Institute]], for which he worked, \"has always been hospitable to Democrats\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/82122/frances-fox-piven-jim-sleeper-and-me |title=Frances Fox Piven, Jim Sleeper and Me |date=January 25, 2011 |last=McWhorter |first=John |work=[[The New Republic]]|accessdate=November 29, 2014}}</ref>  McWhorter has criticized left-wing and activist educators in particular, such as [[Paulo Freire]] and [[Jonathan Kozol]].<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Taking out My Eraser|magazine=[[The New Republic]]|last=McWhorter|first=John|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/politics/taking-out-my-eraser|date=March 5, 2010}}</ref> He believes that [[affirmative action]] should be based on class rather than race.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/12/13/opinions/mcwhorter-antonin-scalia-affirmative-action/ |title=Actually, Scalia had a point. |date=December 13, 2015 |last=McWhorter |first=John |work=[[CNN]]|accessdate=December 3, 2016}}</ref> Political theorist [[Mark Satin]] identifies McWhorter as a [[Radical center (politics)|radical centrist]] thinker.<ref>Satin, Mark (2004).  ''Radical Middle: The Politics We Need Now''. Westview Press and Basic Books, p.&nbsp;10.  {{ISBN|978-0-8133-4190-3}}.</ref> \n\nMcWhorter is an [[atheism|atheist]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/johnhmcwhorter/status/523438726786342912|title=John McWhorter on Twitter|date=October 18, 2014|last=McWhorter|first=John|accessdate=May 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Views on racism ===\nMcWhorter considers that [[anti-racism]] has become as harmful a force in the [[United States]] as [[racism]] itself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://reason.com/video/anti-racism-soho-debate/|title=Has Anti-Racism Become as Harmful as Racism? John McWhorter vs. Nikhil Singh|date=2018-11-30|website=Reason.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://reason.com/2018/11/09/the-message-of-anti-racism-has-become-as/|title=Debate: 'The Message of Anti-Racism Has Become as Harmful a Force in American Life as Racism Itself'|date=2018-11-09|website=Reason.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref> According to him, what is holding blacks back is \"black attitudes\" rather than white racism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.city-journal.org/html/what%E2%80%99s-holding-blacks-back-12025.html|title=What\u2019s Holding Blacks Back?|date=2015-12-23|website=City Journal|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, McWhorter appeared on [[NPR]] and claimed that the use of the word \"thug\" was becoming code for \"the [[Nigger#The N-word euphemism|N-word]]\" or \"black people ruining things\" when used by whites in reference to criminal activity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2015/04/30/403362626/the-racially-charged-meaning-behind-the-word-thug|title=The Racially Charged Meaning Behind The Word 'Thug'|author=All Things Considered|date=April 30, 2015|publisher=NPR|accessdate=November 25, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"WPThug\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/posteverything/wp/2015/05/01/baltimores-mayor-and-president-obama-said-thugs-lets-not-get-too-bent-out-of-shape/?postshare=7831430516681050|title=Baltimore\u2019s mayor and the president said \u2018thugs\u2019? Let\u2019s not get too bent out of shape.|last=McWhorter|first=John|newspaper=The Washington Post|accessdate=November 25, 2015}}</ref> He added that use by [[President Obama]] and former Baltimore Mayor [[Stephanie Rawlings-Blake]] (for which she later apologized) could not be interpreted in the same way, given that the black community's use of \"thug\" may positively connote admiration for black self-direction and survival. McWhorter clarified his views in an article in the ''Washington Post''.<ref name=\"WPThug\" />\n\nMcWhorter has criticized [[microaggression]] and [[white supremacy]] theories,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/32618/microaggression-is-the-new-racism-on-campus/|title='Microaggression' Is the New Racism on Campus|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/4584161/white-supremacy/|title=The Difference Between Racial Bias and White Supremacy|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref> and has argued that [[technology]] cannot be racist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/4475627/is-technology-capable-of-being-racist/|title='Racist' Technology Is a Bug\u2014Not a Crime|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{external media| float = right| video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?162197-1/authentically-black-essays-black-silent-majority ''Booknotes'' interview with McWhorter on ''Authentically Black: Essays for the Black Silent Majority'', March 2, 2003], [[C-SPAN]]| video2 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?202200-1/depth-john-mcwhorter ''In Depth'' interview with McWhorter, March 2, 2008], [[C-SPAN]]}}\n* 1997: ''Towards a New Model of Creole Genesis'' {{ISBN|0-820-43312-8}}\n* 1998: ''Word on the Street: Debunking the Myth of a \"Pure\" Standard English'' {{ISBN|0-738-20446-3}}\n* 2000: ''Spreading the Word: Language and Dialect in America'' {{ISBN|0-325-00198-7}}\n* 2000: ''The Missing Spanish Creoles: Recovering the Birth of Plantation Contact Languages'' {{ISBN|0-520-21999-6}}\n* 2000: ''[[Losing the Race|Losing the Race: Self-Sabotage in Black America]]'' {{ISBN|0-684-83669-6}}\n* 2001: ''The Power of Babel: A Natural History of Language'' {{ISBN|0-06-052085-X}}\n* 2003: ''Authentically Black: Essays for the Black Silent Majority'' {{ISBN|1-592-40001-9}}\n* 2003: ''Doing Our Own Thing: The Degradation of Language and Music and Why We Should, Like, Care'' {{ISBN|1-592-40016-