{"title_page": "Wakatake-class destroyer", "text_new": "{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Kuretake2.jpg\n|Ship caption=The ''Wakatake''-class destroyer ''Kuretake''\n}}\n{{Infobox ship class overview\n|Name=''Wakatake'' class\n|Builders=*[[Kawasaki Shipbuilding Corporation|Kawasaki Shipbuilding]]\n*[[Maizuru Naval Arsenal]]\n*[[Fujinagata Shipyards]]\n*[[IHI Corporation|Ishikawajima Shipyards]]\n|Operators={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|Class before={{sclass-|Minekaze|destroyer|4}}\n|Class after={{sclass-|Kamikaze|destroyer (1922)|4}}\n|Subclasses=\n|Built range=\n|In commission range= 1920\u20131945\n|Total ships planned=13\n|Total ships completed=8\n|Total ships cancelled=5\n|Total ships lost=7\n|Total ships retired=1\n|Total ships preserved=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship type=[[Destroyer]]\n|Ship displacement=*{{convert|900|LT|t|lk=in}} normal,\n*{{convert|1100|LT|t|abbr=on}} full load\n|Ship length=*{{convert|83.8|m|ft|abbr=on}} [[Length between perpendiculars|pp]],\n*{{convert|85.3|m|ft|abbr=on}} overall\n|Ship beam={{convert|7.9|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draught={{convert|2.5|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n|Ship propulsion=2-shaft Mitsubishi-[[Parsons Marine Steam Turbine Company|Parsons geared steam turbine]], 3 heavy oil-fired boilers {{convert|21500|ihp|kW|lk=in|abbr=on}}\n|Ship speed={{convert|36|kn|km/h|lk=in}}\n|Ship range={{Convert|3000|nmi|km|abbr=on}} at {{Convert|15|kn|abbr=on}} \n|Ship complement=110\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=*3 \u00d7 [[Type 3 120 mm 45 caliber naval gun]]\n*2 \u00d7 7.7mm machine guns\n*4 \u00d7 53cm [[torpedo]]es\n*20 \u00d7 [[naval mine|mines]]\n*(''Asagao'', after July 1944)\n*2 \u00d7 [[Type 3 120 mm 45 caliber naval gun]]s\n*4 \u00d7 [[Type 96 25 mm AT/AA Gun]]s,\n*4 \u00d7 [[Hotchkiss M1929 machine gun|{{convert|13.2|mm|in|abbr=on}}]] Type 93 AA guns,\n*2 \u00d7 {{convert|530|mm|in|abbr=on}} 6th Year Type [[torpedo tube|TT]]s\n*(3 \u00d7 [[Imperial Japanese Navy Technical Department#6th Year Type Torpedo .281917.29|6th Year Type]] [[torpedo]]es)\n*up to 36 \u00d7 [[depth charge]]s\n|Ship armor=\n|Ship armour=\n|Ship aircraft=\n|Ship aircraft facilities=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|} \nThe {{nihongo|'''''Wakatake''-class destroyers'''|\u82e5\u7af9\u578b\u99c6\u9010\u8266|Wakatakegata kuchikukan}} were a [[ship class|class]] of eight second-class [[destroyer]]s of the [[Imperial Japanese Navy]].<ref>Jentsura, ''Warships of the Imperial Japanese Navy, 1869-1945''</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe medium-sized ''Wakatake''-class destroyers were a follow-on to the {{sclass-|Momi|destroyer|4}} as part of the Imperial Japanese Navy's [[Eight-eight fleet|8-6 Fleet Program]] from fiscal 1921 as a lower cost accompaniment to the larger {{sclass-|Minekaze|destroyer|2}}s. The class was originally planned to consist of thirteen vessels, but due to the [[Washington Naval Treaty]], as well as budgetary limitations, the orders for the last four were cancelled in 1922, with the final number being reduced to eight when ''No.14'' was also cancelled. The ''Wakatake'' class was the last class to be rated \"second class\" and all future destroyers were designed larger.<ref>Globalsecurity.org, IJN Wakatake class destroyers</ref> It was planned that the ''Wakatake''-class ships should have names, but upon completion they were given numbers. This proved to be extremely unpopular with the crews and was a constant source of confusion in communications, so in 1928, names were assigned.<ref>Howarth, ''The Fighting Ships of the Rising Sun''</ref>\n\n==Design==\nThe ''Wakatake''-class destroyers were essentially slightly modified ''Momi''-class ships with 50 tons additional displacement and a deeper draft to improve handling characteristics in heavy seas, particularly against rolling. Weaponry layout (with the exception of added AA armaments), general arrangement and silhouette were all identical with the ''Momi'' class.\n\nAs with the ''Momi'' class, a number of types of [[turbine engine]]s were used for propulsion. ''Asagao'' was built with [[Parsons Marine Steam Turbine Company|Parsons]] impulse turbines, ''Y\u016bgao'' with [[Escher Wyss & Cie]] Zoelly turbines, and the remaining vessels with [[John Brown & Company|Brown-Curtis]] turbines.\n\nThe armament for the ''Wakatake''-class was identical to that of the ''Momi'' class. The [[main battery]] consisted of three [[Type 3 120 mm 45 caliber naval gun]]s in single mounts, with two twin Type 6 torpedo launchers. Anti-aircraft protection was provided by two 7.7mm machine guns. After the start of the [[Pacific War]], one of the Type 3 guns was replaced by two triple-mount [[Type 96 25 mm AT/AA Gun|Type 96]] 25-mm cannons, although some vessels had three twin-mounts and two single-mounts instead. The minesweeping gear was replaced by 36 to 48 [[depth charge]]s with four launchers. Some of the vessels also were fitted with a Type 13 radar.<ref name=\"Stille\">{{cite book |last1=Stille |first1=Mark |title=Imperial Japanese Navy Antisubmarine Escorts 1941\u201345 |date=2017 |publisher=Osprey Publishing |location=Oxford, UK |isbn=978 1 4728 1817 1 |pages=14\u201317}}</ref>\n\n==Operational history==\nThe small displacement of the ''Wakatake''-class limited their utility as fleet escorts, and as with the ''Momi''-class, they were mainly used in Chinese coastal waters, where their shallow draft made them suitable for operations in rivers and coastal waters.<ref name=\"Stille\"/>\n\nOn 15 September 1932, {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Sawarabi||2}} capsized due to poor stability and sank north of [[Keelung]] near [[Taiwan]]. In April 1940 {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Y\u016bgao||2}} was re-rated as ''Patrol Boat No. 46'', with considerably reduced armament and the removal of one boiler, which reduced her speed to only 18 knots.<ref name=\"Stille\"/>\n\nOf the remaining six units, three (''Wakatake'', ''Kuretake'', and ''Sanae'') were assigned to Destroyer Division 13  under the [[Kure Naval District]], and patrolled the [[Seto Inland Sea]] and the [[Bungo Strait]] on [[anti-submarine warfare|antisubmarine patrols]]. The other three (''Asagao'', ''Fuy\u014d'' and ''Karukaya'')were assigned to Destroyer Division 32 under the [[Chinkai Guard District]], which was assigned to patrol the [[Tsushima Strait]] screening maritime traffic in the [[Tsushima Straits]]. From 10 April 1942, the 1st Surface Escort Division of the [[Southwest Area Fleet]] was created, and Desdivs 13 and 32 were assigned to it to provide protection for convoys against [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] submarine activity. The convoy routes were initially those between [[Moji-ku, Kitaky\u016bsh\u016b|Moji]], Taiwan, and the [[Philippines]]. Later, these routes extended to [[Singapore]], [[French Indochina]], the [[Netherlands East Indies]], and [[Palau]]. In the course of this service, {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Karukaya||2}} set a record by successfully completing 54 convoy escorts before her loss. Of the six destroyers, four were lost to American submarines, and one to an air attack. Only {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Asagao||2}} survived the war and was finally broken up in 1948.<ref>Nevitt, Combined Fleet.com</ref>\n\n==List of Ships==\n{{clear}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:97%;\"\n|-\n!width=\"10%\"| Kanji\n!Name\n!Builder\n!Laid down\n!Launched\n!Completed\n!width=\"38%\"|Fate\n|-\n| \u82e5\u7af9<br/>(\u7b2c\u4e8c\u99c6\u9010\u8266)\n| {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Wakatake||2}}<br/>ex-''No.2''\n| [[Kawasaki Shipbuilding Corporation|Kawasaki Shipyards]], [[Japan]]\n| 13 December 1921\n| 24 July 1922\n| 30 September 1922\n| Sunk 30 March 1944 in air attack off Palau [07.50N, 134.20E]; struck 10 May 1944\n|-\n|\u5449\u7af9<br/>(\u7b2c\u56db\u99c6\u9010\u8266)\n| {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Kuretake||2}}<br/>ex-''No.4''\n| [[Maizuru Naval Arsenal]], Japan\n| 15 March 1922\n| 21 October 1922\n| 21 December 1922\n| Sunk 30 December 1944 by {{USS|Razorback|SS-394|6}} at [[Bashi Channel]] [21N, 121.24E]; struck 10 February  1945\n|- \n| \u65e9\u82d7<br>(\u7b2c\u516d\u99c6\u9010\u8266)\n| {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Sanae||2}}<br/>ex-''No.6''\n| [[Uraga Dock Company]], Japan\n| 5 April 1922\n| 15 February 1923\n| 5 November 1923\n| Torpedoed Celebes Sea [04.52N, 122.07E] 1943-11-13 by {{USS|Bluefish|SS-222|6}}; struck 5 January 1944\n|- \n| \u65e9\u8568<br>(\u7b2c\u516b\u99c6\u9010\u8266)\n| {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Sawarabi||2}}<br/>ex-''No.8''\n| Uraga Dock Company, Japan\n| 20 November 1922\n| 1 September 1923\n| 24 July 1924\n| Capsized 5 December 1932 in storm off Keelung, Taiwan [27.17N, 122.12E]; struck 1 April 1933\n|- \n| \u671d\u9854<br>(\u7b2c\u5341\u99c6\u9010\u8266)\n| {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Asagao||2}}<br/>ex-''No.10''\n| [[IHI Corporation|Ishikawajima Shipyards]], Japan\n| 14 March 1922\n| 4 November 1922\n| 10 May 1923\n| Sunk 22 August 1945 by [[naval mine]] at [[Kanmon Straits]]; raised, BU 1948\n|- \n| \u5915\u9854<br>(\u7b2c\u5341\u4e8c\u99c6\u9010\u8266)\n| {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Y\u016bgao||2}}<br/>ex-''No.12''\n| Ishikawajima Shipyards, Japan\n| 15 May 1922\n| 14 April 1923\n| 31 May 1924\n| Converted 1 February 1940 to {{nihongo|''Patrol Boat No. 46''|\u7b2c\u56db\u516d\u53f7\u54e8\u6212\u8247|Dai-46-G\u014d sh\u014dkaitei}}; sunk 10 November 1944 by {{USS|Greenling|SS-213|6}} at [[:ja:\u77f3\u5eca\u5d0e|Ir\u014dzaki]]\n|-\n| \u8299\u84c9<br>(\u7b2c\u5341\u516d\u99c6\u9010\u8266)\n| {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Fuy\u014d||2}}<br/>ex-''No.16''\n| [[Fujinagata Shipyards]], Japan\n| 16 February 1922\n| 23 September 1922\n| 16 March 1923\n| Torpedoed 20 December 1943 off Manila Bay [14.44N, 119.55E] by {{USS|Puffer|SS-268|6}}; struck 5 February 1944\n|-\n| \u5208\u8431<br/>(\u7b2c\u5341\u516b\u99c6\u9010\u8266)\n| {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Karukaya||2}}<br/>ex-''No.18''\n| [[Fujinagata Shipyards]], [[Japan]]\n| 16 May 1922\n| 19 March 1923\n| 20 August 1923\n| Torpedoed 10 May 1944 west of Luzon [15.38N, 119.25E] by {{USS|Cod|SS-224|6}}; struck 10 July 1944\n|-\n|}\n\nThe five cancelled units were initially to be named ''Shian'' (from Kawasaki, Kobe)(later ''No.14''), ''Omodoka'' (also from Kawasaki, Kobe)(later ''No.20''), ''Nadeshiko'' (from Fujinagata Zosensho, Osaka)(later ''No.22''), ''Botan'' (from Uraga Dock Co, Tokyo)(later ''No.24'') and ''Basho'' (from Ishikawajima Zosensho, Tokyo)(later ''No.26'').\n\n==Naming history==\nThe IJN originally planned that the ''Wakatake''-class ships should have names, but upon completion they were given numbers due to the projected large number of warships the IJN expected to build through the [[Eight-eight fleet]] plan. This proved to be extremely unpopular with the crews and was a constant source of confusion in communications. In August 1928, names were assigned, but not the original names that were planned.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" width=\"60%\"\n|width=\"13%\"|'''Plan name and transliteration'''\n|width=\"18%\"|'''Original name as ordered'''\n|width=\"17%\"|'''Renamed 24 April 1924'''\n|width=\"17%\"|'''Renamed 1 August 1928'''\n|-\n|{{nihongo|''Kiky\u014d''|\u6854\u6897}}<br/>[[Chinese bellflower]]\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-2 Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u4e8c\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''2nd Destroyer''\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-2-G\u014d Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u4e8c\u53f7\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''No.2 Destroyer''\n|{{nihongo|''Wakatake''|\u82e5\u7af9}},<br/>Bamboo sprout\n|-\n|{{nihongo|''Yuri''|\u767e\u5408}},<br/>[[Lilium]]\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-4 Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u56db\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''4th Destroyer''\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-4-G\u014d Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u56db\u53f7\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''No.4 Destroyer''\n|{{nihongo|''[[Kuretake]]''|\u5449\u7af9}},<br/>Black bamboo, ''Phyllostachys nigra''\n|-\n|{{nihongo|''Ayame''|\u83d6\u84b2}}<br/>''[[Iris sanguinea]]''\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-6 Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u516d\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''6th Destroyer''\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-6-G\u014d Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u516d\u53f7\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''No.6 Destroyer''\n|{{nihongo|''Sanae''|\u65e9\u82d7}},<br/>Rice sprouts on May\n|-\n|{{nihongo|''Kaid\u014d''|\u6d77\u68e0}}<br/>[[:de:Halls Apfel|Malus halliana]]\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-8 Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u516b\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''8th Destroyer''\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-8-G\u014d Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u516b\u53f7\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''No.8 Destroyer''\n|{{nihongo|''Sawarabi''|\u65e9\u8568}},<br/>[[Bracken]] on Spring\n|-\n|{{nihongo|''Kakitsubata''|\u675c\u82e5}}<br/>''[[Iris laevigata]]''\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-10 Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u5341\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''10th Destroyer''\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-10-G\u014d Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u5341\u53f7\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''No.10 Destroyer''\n|{{nihongo|''Asagao''|\u671d\u9854}},<br/>[[Morning glory]]\n|-\n|{{nihongo|''Tsutsuji''|\u8e91\u8e85}}<br/>[[Azalea]]\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-12 Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u5341\u4e8c\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''12th Destroyer''\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-12-G\u014d Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u5341\u4e8c\u53f7\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''No.12 Destroyer''\n|{{nihongo|''Y\u016bgao''|\u5915\u9854}},<br/>[[Ipomoea alba]]\n|-\n|{{nihongo|''Shion''|\u7d2b\u82d1}},<br/>[[Aster tataricus]]\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-14 Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u5341\u56db\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''14th Destroyer''\n| \n| \n|-\n|{{nihongo|''Ajisai''|\u7d2b\u967d}}<br/>[[Hydrangea]]\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-16 Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u5341\u516d\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''16th Destroyer''\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-16-G\u014d Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u5341\u516d\u53f7\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''No.16 Destroyer''\n|{{nihongo|''Fuy\u014d''|\u8299\u84c9}},<br/>[[Hibiscus mutabilis]]\n|-\n|{{nihongo|''Karukaya''|\u5208\u8431}}<br/>One of the [[Poaceae]]\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-18 Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u5341\u516b\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''18th Destroyer''\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-18-G\u014d Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u5341\u516b\u53f7\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''No.18 Destroyer''\n|{{nihongo|''Karukaya''|\u5208\u8431}},<br/>One of several [[Andropogoneae]] grasses used for [[thatching]]\n|-\n|{{nihongo|''Omodaka''|\u6ca2\u7009}},<br/>[[Alismataceae]]\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-20 Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u4e8c\u5341\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''20th Destroyer''\n|\n|\n|-\n|{{nihongo|''Botan''|\u7261\u4e39}},<br/>[[Peony]]\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-22 Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u4e8c\u5341\u4e8c\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''22nd Destroyer''\n|\n|\n|-\n|{{nihongo|''Bash\u014d''|\u82ad\u8549}},<br/>[[Musa basjoo]]\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-24 Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u4e8c\u5341\u56db\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''24th Destroyer''\n| \n| \n|-\n|{{nihongo|''Nadeshiko''|\u64ab\u5b50}},<br/>[[Dianthus]]\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-26 Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u4e8c\u5341\u516d\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''26th Destroyer''\n|\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Books===\n*{{cite book\n | last = Evans\n | first = David\n | year = 1979\n | title = Kaigun: Strategy, Tactics, and Technology in the Imperial Japanese Navy, 1887\u20131941\n | publisher = US Naval Institute Press\n | location =\n | isbn = 0-87021-192-7\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | last = Howarth\n | first = Stephen\n | year = 1983\n | title = The Fighting Ships of the Rising Sun: The Drama of the Imperial Japanese Navy, 1895\u20131945\n | publisher = Atheneum\n | location =\n | isbn = 0-689-11402-8\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | last = Jentsura\n | first = Hansgeorg\n | year = 1976\n | title = Warships of the Imperial Japanese Navy, 1869\u20131945\n | publisher = US Naval Institute Press\n | location =\n | isbn = 0-87021-893-X\n}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Watts |first1=A.J. |title=Japanese warships of World War II |date=1966 |publisher=Ian Allan |isbn=0711002150}}\n''Collection of writings by Sizuo Fukui Vol.5, Stories of Japanese Destroyers'', K\u014djinsha (Japan) 1993, {{ISBN|4-7698-0611-6}}\n*''Model Art Ship Modelling Special No.17, Genealogy of Japanese Destroyers Part-1'', Model Art Co. Ltd. (Japan), September 2005, Book code 08734-9\n*''Model Art Extra No.340, Drawings of Imperial Japanese Naval Vessels Part-1'', Model Art Co. Ltd. (Japan), October 1989, Book code 08734-10\n*Daiji Katagiri, ''Ship Name Chronicles of the Imperial Japanese Navy [[Combined Fleet]]'', K\u014djinsha (Japan), June 1988, {{ISBN|4-7698-0386-9}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Wakatake class destroyers}}\n*{{cite web\n| last = Nishida\n| first = Hiroshi\n| url = http://homepage2.nifty.com/nishidah/e/stc0419.htm\n| title = Materials of IJN: Minekaze class destroyer\n| work = Imperial Japanese Navy\n}}\n*{{cite web\n| last = Globalsecurity.org\n| first =\n| url = http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/japan/wakatake-dd.htm\n| title = IJN Wakatake class destroyers\n| work =\n}}\n*{{cite web\n| last = Nevitt\n| first = Allyn D\n| url = http://www.combinedfleet.com/alsoserv.htm\n| title = They Also Served: The Second-Class Destroyers\n| work = Combined Fleet.com\n}}\n\n<!-- non-breaking space to keep AWB drones from altering the space before the navbox-->\n\n{{Wakatake class destroyers}}\n{{WWII Japanese Ships}}\n\n[[Category:Destroyer classes]]\n[[Category:Wakatake-class destroyers| ]]\n[[Category:World War II destroyers of Japan]]\n", "text_old": "{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Kuretake2.jpg\n|Ship caption=The ''Wakatake''-class destroyer ''Kuretake''\n}}\n{{Infobox ship class overview\n|Name=''Wakatake'' class\n|Builders=*[[Kawasaki Shipbuilding Corporation|Kawasaki Shipbuilding]]\n*[[Maizuru Naval Arsenal]]\n*[[Fujinagata Shipyards]]\n*[[IHI Corporation|Ishikawajima Shipyards]]\n|Operators={{navy|Empire of Japan}}\n|Class before={{sclass-|Minekaze|destroyer|4}}\n|Class after={{sclass-|Kamikaze|destroyer (1922)|4}}\n|Subclasses=\n|Built range=\n|In commission range= 1920\u20131945\n|Total ships planned=13\n|Total ships completed=8\n|Total ships cancelled=5\n|Total ships lost=7\n|Total ships retired=1\n|Total ships preserved=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship type=[[Destroyer]]\n|Ship displacement=*{{convert|900|LT|t|lk=in}} normal,\n*{{convert|1100|LT|t|abbr=on}} full load\n|Ship length=*{{convert|83.8|m|ft|abbr=on}} [[Length between perpendiculars|pp]],\n*{{convert|85.3|m|ft|abbr=on}} overall\n|Ship beam={{convert|7.9|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draught={{convert|2.5|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n|Ship propulsion=2-shaft Mitsubishi-[[Parsons Marine Steam Turbine Company|Parsons geared steam turbine]], 3 heavy oil-fired boilers {{convert|21500|ihp|kW|lk=in|abbr=on}}\n|Ship speed={{convert|36|kn|km/h|lk=in}}\n|Ship range={{Convert|3000|nmi|km|abbr=on}} at {{Convert|15|kn|abbr=on}} \n|Ship complement=110\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=*3 \u00d7 [[Type 3 120 mm 45 caliber naval gun]]\n*2 \u00d7 7.7mm machine guns\n*4 \u00d7 53cm [[torpedo]]es\n*20 \u00d7 [[naval mine|mines]]\n*(''Asagao'', after July 1944)\n*2 \u00d7 [[Type 3 120 mm 45 caliber naval gun]]s\n*4 \u00d7 [[Type 96 25 mm AT/AA Gun]]s,\n*4 \u00d7 [[Hotchkiss M1929 machine gun|{{convert|13.2|mm|in|abbr=on}}]] Type 93 AA guns,\n*2 \u00d7 {{convert|530|mm|in|abbr=on}} 6th Year Type [[torpedo tube|TT]]s\n*(3 \u00d7 [[Imperial Japanese Navy Technical Department#6th Year Type Torpedo .281917.29|6th Year Type]] [[torpedo]]es)\n*up to 36 \u00d7 [[depth charge]]s\n|Ship armor=\n|Ship armour=\n|Ship aircraft=\n|Ship aircraft facilities=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|} \nThe {{nihongo|'''''Wakatake''-class destroyers'''|\u82e5\u7af9\u578b\u99c6\u9010\u8266|Wakatakegata kuchikukan}} were a [[ship class|class]] of eight second-class [[destroyer]]s of the [[Imperial Japanese Navy]].<ref>Jentsura, ''Warships of the Imperial Japanese Navy, 1869-1945''</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe medium-sized ''Wakatake''-class destroyers were a follow-on to the {{sclass-|Momi|destroyer|4}} as part of the Imperial Japanese Navy's [[Eight-eight fleet|8-6 Fleet Program]] from fiscal 1921 as a lower cost accompaniment to the larger {{sclass-|Minekaze|destroyer|2}}s. The class was originally planned to consist of thirteen vessels, but due to the [[Washington Naval Treaty]], as well as budgetary limitations, the orders for the last four were cancelled in 1922, with the final number being reduced to eight when ''No.14'' was also cancelled. The ''Wakatake'' class was the last class to be rated \"second class\" and all future destroyers were designed larger.<ref>Globalsecurity.org, IJN Wakatake class destroyers</ref> It was planned that the ''Wakatake''-class ships should have names, but upon completion they were given numbers. This proved to be extremely unpopular with the crews and was a constant source of confusion in communications, so in 1928, names were assigned.<ref>Howarth, ''The Fighting Ships of the Rising Sun''</ref>\n\n==Design==\nThe ''Wakatake''-class destroyers were essentially slightly modified ''Momi''-class ships with 50 tons additional displacement and a deeper draft to improve handling characteristics in heavy seas, particularly against rolling. Weaponry layout (with the exception of added AA armaments), general arrangement and silhouette were all identical with the ''Momi'' class.\n\nAs with the ''Momi'' class, a number of types of [[turbine engine]]s were used for propulsion. ''Asagao'' was built with [[Parsons Marine Steam Turbine Company|Parsons]] impulse turbines, ''Y\u016bgao'' with [[Escher Wyss & Cie]] Zoelly turbines, and the remaining vessels with [[John Brown & Company|Brown-Curtis]] turbines.\n\nThe armament for the ''Wakatake''-class was identical to that of the ''Momi'' class. The [[main battery]] consisted of three [[Type 3 120 mm 45 caliber naval gun]]s in single mounts, with two twin Type 6 torpedo launchers. Anti-aircraft protection was provided by two 7.7mm machine guns. After the start of the [[Pacific War]], one of the Type 3 guns was replaced by two triple-mount [[Type 96 25 mm AT/AA Gun|Type 96]] 25-mm cannons, although some vessels had three twin-mounts and two single-mounts instead. The minesweeping gear was replaced by 36 to 48 [[depth charge]]s with four launchers. Some of the vessels also were fitted with a Type 13 radar.<ref name=\"Stille\">{{cite book |last1=Stille |first1=Mark |title=Imperial Japanese Navy Antisubmarine Escorts 1941\u201345 |date=2017 |publisher=Osprey Publishing |location=Oxford, UK |isbn=978 1 4728 1817 1 |pages=14\u201317}}</ref>\n\n==Operational history==\nThe small displacement of the ''Wakatake''-class limited their utility as fleet escorts, and as with the ''Momi''-class, they were mainly used in Chinese coastal waters, where their shallow draft made them suitable for operations in rivers and coastal waters.<ref name=\"Stille\"/>\n\nOn 15 September 1932, {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Sawarabi||2}} capsized due to poor stability and sank north of [[Keelung]] near [[Taiwan]]. In April 1940 {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Y\u016bgao||2}} was re-rated as ''Patrol Boat No. 46'', with considerably reduced armament and the removal of one boiler, which reduced her speed to only 18 knots.<ref name=\"Stille\"/>\n\nOf the remaining six units, three (''Wakatake'', ''Kuretake'', and ''Sanae'') were assigned to Destroyer Division 13  under the [[Kure Naval District]], and patrolled the [[Seto Inland Sea]] and the [[Bungo Strait]] on [[anti-submarine warfare|antisubmarine patrols]]. The other three (''Asagao'', ''Fuy\u014d'' and ''Karukaya'')were assigned to Destroyer Division 32 under the [[Chinkai Guard District]], which was assigned to patrol the [[Tsushima Strait]] screening maritime traffic in the [[Tsushima Straits]]. From 10 April 1942, the 1st Surface Escort Division of the [[Southwest Area Fleet]] was created, and Desdivs 13 and 32 were assigned to it to provide protection for convoys against [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] submarine activity. The convoy routes were initially those between [[Moji-ku, Kitaky\u016bsh\u016b|Moji]], Taiwan, and the [[Philippines]]. Later, these routes extended to [[Singapore]], [[French Indochina]], the [[Netherlands East Indies]], and [[Palau]]. In the course of this service, {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Karukaya||2}} set a record by successfully completing 54 convoy escorts before her loss. Of the six destroyers, four were lost to American submarines, and one to an air attack. Only {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Asagao||2}} survived the war and was finally broken up in 1948.<ref>Nevitt, Combined Fleet.com</ref>\n\n==List of Ships==\n{{clear}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:97%;\"\n|-\n!width=\"10%\"| Kanji\n!Name\n!Builder\n!Laid down\n!Launched\n!Completed\n!width=\"38%\"|Fate\n|-\n| \u82e5\u7af9<br/>(\u7b2c\u4e8c\u99c6\u9010\u8266)\n| {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Wakatake||2}}<br/>ex-''No.2''\n| [[Kawasaki Shipbuilding Corporation|Kawasaki Shipyards]], [[Japan]]\n| 13 December 1921\n| 24 July 1922\n| 30 September 1922\n| Sunk 30 March 1944 in air attack off Palau [07.50N, 134.20E]; struck 10 May 1944\n|-\n|\u5449\u7af9<br/>(\u7b2c\u56db\u99c6\u9010\u8266)\n| {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Kuretake||2}}<br/>ex-''No.4''\n| [[Maizuru Naval Arsenal]], Japan\n| 15 March 1922\n| 21 October 1922\n| 21 December 1922\n| Sunk 30 December 1944 by {{USS|Razorback|SS-394|6}} at [[Bashi Channel]] [21N, 121.24E]; struck 10 February  1945\n|- \n| \u65e9\u82d7<br>(\u7b2c\u516d\u99c6\u9010\u8266)\n| {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Sanae||2}}<br/>ex-''No.6''\n| [[Uraga Dock Company]], Japan\n| 5 April 1922\n| 15 February 1923\n| 5 November 1923\n| Torpedoed Celebes Sea [04.52N, 122.07E] 1943-11-13 by {{USS|Bluefish|SS-222|6}}; struck 5 January 1944\n|- \n| \u65e9\u8568<br>(\u7b2c\u516b\u99c6\u9010\u8266)\n| {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Sawarabi||2}}<br/>ex-''No.8''\n| Uraga Dock Company, Japan\n| 20 November 1922\n| 1 September 1923\n| 24 July 1924\n| Capsized 5 December 1932 in storm off Keelung, Taiwan [27.17N, 122.12E]; struck 1 April 1933\n|- \n| \u671d\u9854<br>(\u7b2c\u5341\u99c6\u9010\u8266)\n| {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Asagao||2}}<br/>ex-''No.10''\n| [[IHI Corporation|Ishikawajima Shipyards]], Japan\n| 14 March 1922\n| 4 November 1922\n| 10 May 1923\n| Sunk 22 August 1945 by [[naval mine]] at [[Kanmon Straits]]; raised, BU 1948\n|- \n| \u5915\u9854<br>(\u7b2c\u5341\u4e8c\u99c6\u9010\u8266)\n| {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Y\u016bgao||2}}<br/>ex-''No.12''\n| Ishikawajima Shipyards, Japan\n| 15 May 1922\n| 14 April 1923\n| 31 May 1924\n| Converted 1 February 1940 to {{nihongo|''Patrol Boat No. 46''|\u7b2c\u56db\u516d\u53f7\u54e8\u6212\u8247|Dai-46-G\u014d sh\u014dkaitei}}; sunk 10 November 1944 by {{USS|Greenling|SS-213|6}} at [[:ja:\u77f3\u5eca\u5d0e|Ir\u014dzaki]]\n|-\n| \u8299\u84c9<br>(\u7b2c\u5341\u516d\u99c6\u9010\u8266)\n| {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Fuy\u014d||2}}<br/>ex-''No.16''\n| [[Fujinagata Shipyards]], Japan\n| 16 February 1922\n| 23 September 1922\n| 16 March 1923\n| Torpedoed 20 December 1943 off Manila Bay [14.44N, 119.55E] by {{USS|Puffer|SS-268|6}}; struck 5 February 1944\n|-\n| \u5208\u8431<br/>(\u7b2c\u5341\u516b\u99c6\u9010\u8266)\n| {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Karukaya||2}}<br/>ex-''No.18''\n| [[Fujinagata Shipyards]], [[Japan]]\n| 16 May 1922\n| 19 March 1923\n| 20 August 1923\n| Torpedoed 10 May 1944 west of Luzon [15.38N, 119.25E] by {{USS|Cod|SS-224|6}}; struck 10 July 1944\n|-\n|}\n\nThe five cancelled units were initially to be named ''Shian'' (from Kawasaki, Kobe)(later ''No.14''), ''Omodoka'' (also from Kawasaki, Kobe)(later ''No.20''), ''Nadeshiko'' (from Fujinagata Zosensho, Osaka)(later ''No.22''), ''Botan'' (from Uraga Dock Co, Tokyo)(later ''No.24'') and ''Basho'' (from Ishikawajima Zosensho, Tokyo)(later ''No.26'').\n\n==Naming history==\nThe IJN originally planned that the ''Wakatake''-class ships should have names, but upon completion they were given numbers due to the projected large number of warships the IJN expected to build through the [[Eight-eight fleet]] plan. This proved to be extremely unpopular with the crews and was a constant source of confusion in communications. In August 1928, names were assigned, but not the original names that were planned.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" width=\"60%\"\n|width=\"13%\"|'''Plan name and transliteration'''\n|width=\"18%\"|'''Original name as ordered'''\n|width=\"17%\"|'''Renamed 24 April 1924'''\n|width=\"17%\"|'''Renamed 1 August 1928'''\n|-\n|{{nihongo|''Kiky\u014d''|\u6854\u6897}}<br/>[[Chinese bellflower]]\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-2 Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u4e8c\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''2nd Destroyer''\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-2-G\u014d Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u4e8c\u53f7\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''No.2 Destroyer''\n|{{nihongo|''Wakatake''|\u82e5\u7af9}},<br/>Bamboo sprout\n|-\n|{{nihongo|''Yuri''|\u767e\u5408}},<br/>[[Lilium]]\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-4 Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u56db\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''4th Destroyer''\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-4-G\u014d Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u56db\u53f7\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''No.4 Destroyer''\n|{{nihongo|''[[Kuretake]]''|\u5449\u7af9}},<br/>Black bamboo, ''Phyllostachys nigra''\n|-\n|{{nihongo|''Ayame''|\u83d6\u84b2}}<br/>''[[Iris sanguinea]]''\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-6 Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u516d\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''6th Destroyer''\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-6-G\u014d Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u516d\u53f7\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''No.6 Destroyer''\n|{{nihongo|''Sanae''|\u65e9\u82d7}},<br/>Rice sprouts on May\n|-\n|{{nihongo|''Kaid\u014d''|\u6d77\u68e0}}<br/>[[:de:Halls Apfel|Malus halliana]]\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-8 Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u516b\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''8th Destroyer''\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-8-G\u014d Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u516b\u53f7\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''No.8 Destroyer''\n|{{nihongo|''Sawarabi''|\u65e9\u8568}},<br/>[[Bracken]] on Spring\n|-\n|{{nihongo|''Kakitsubata''|\u675c\u82e5}}<br/>''[[Iris laevigata]]''\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-10 Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u5341\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''10th Destroyer''\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-10-G\u014d Kuchikukan''<br/>|\u7b2c\u5341\u53f7\u99c6\u9010\u8266}},<br/>''No.10 Destroyer''\n|{{nihongo|''Asagao''|\u671d\u9854}},<br/>[[Morning glory]]\n|-\n|{{nihongo|''Tsutsuji''|\u8e91\u8e85}}<br/>[[Azalea]]\n|{{nihongo|''Dai-12 Kuchikuka